WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:12.768 --> 00:00:15.366
Joan Blades: Do you have politically diverse friends?
琼·布雷兹：你有政见不同的朋友吗？

2
00:00:15.745 --> 00:00:17.397
What do you talk about with them?
你会跟他们聊些什么？

3
00:00:17.896 --> 00:00:20.726
I'm a progressive; I live in a town full of progressives,
我是一个进步派， 我生活的地方全是进步派，

4
00:00:20.750 --> 00:00:24.398
and 15 years ago, I didn't have any conservative friends.
15年前，我的朋友中 没有一个是保守党。

5
00:00:24.422 --> 00:00:27.186
Now I have a wonderful mix of friends,
而现在我的朋友各种各样，

6
00:00:27.210 --> 00:00:28.597
and they include John.
包括约翰。

7
00:00:29.174 --> 00:00:30.927
John Gable: I am not a progressive.
约翰·盖博：我不是进步派。

8
00:00:31.492 --> 00:00:34.371
I'm a Republican who grew up in a Republican family
我是共和党人， 出生在一个共和党家庭，

9
00:00:34.395 --> 00:00:35.676
in the conservative South,
来自保守的南方，

10
00:00:35.700 --> 00:00:39.380
and even worked in Republican politics, locally and at the national level.
甚至一直在共和党做事， 之前在老家，后来到了全国级别。

11
00:00:39.404 --> 00:00:41.952
But the last 24 years, I've been in technology
但在过去的24年间， 我从事技术工作，

12
00:00:41.976 --> 00:00:44.279
and living in a very progressive area.
生活在进步派地区。

13
00:00:44.303 --> 00:00:46.203
So I have a lot of progressive friends,
因此我有许多进步派的朋友，

14
00:00:46.227 --> 00:00:47.660
including Joan.
包括琼。

15
00:00:48.486 --> 00:00:50.990
JB: I was born in Berkeley, California,
JB：我出生在加州的伯克利，

16
00:00:51.014 --> 00:00:53.497
a notoriously progressive college town.
众所周知，那里是 进步主义盛行的大学城。

17
00:00:54.119 --> 00:00:55.808
And I live there now.
我现在也住在那儿。

18
00:00:56.711 --> 00:01:02.410
In 1998, six months into the Monica Lewinsky-Clinton impeachment scandal,
1998年，莱温斯基和克林顿的丑闻 进行到第6个月。

19
00:01:02.434 --> 00:01:06.991
I helped cofound MoveOn.org with a one-sentence petition:
我参与共建了MoveOn.org网站， 有一句请愿的话：

20
00:01:07.015 --> 00:01:10.322
"Congress must immediately censure the president
“国会必须立即谴责总统，

21
00:01:10.346 --> 00:01:13.303
and move on to pressing issues facing the nation."
并转而处理国家面临的 更紧迫问题。”

22
00:01:13.327 --> 00:01:16.903
Now, that was actually a very unifying petition in many ways.
从很多方面来看， 那是一句非常有凝聚力的谴责。

23
00:01:16.927 --> 00:01:19.145
You could love Clinton or hate Clinton
无论你对克林顿是爱是恨，

24
00:01:19.169 --> 00:01:23.146
and agree that the best thing for the country was to move on.
都会认同，对于国家而言， 最好的方法就是继续前进。

25
00:01:23.678 --> 00:01:28.253
As the leader of MoveOn, I saw the polarization just continue.
作为MoveOn的领头人， 我看到两极分化在持续。

26
00:01:28.277 --> 00:01:30.209
And I found myself wondering
我不禁在想，

27
00:01:31.377 --> 00:01:33.860
why I saw things so differently
为什么我看待事情的方式，

28
00:01:33.884 --> 00:01:36.561
than many people in other parts of the country.
跟这个国家其他地方的人会不一样。

29
00:01:36.585 --> 00:01:42.791
So in 2005, when I had an opportunity to get together with grassroots leaders
于是在2005年，当我有机会 接触一些草根领袖

30
00:01:42.815 --> 00:01:45.022
across the political divide,
我们政见不同，

31
00:01:45.046 --> 00:01:46.512
I grabbed it.
我抓住了这个机会。

32
00:01:46.964 --> 00:01:49.670
And I became friends with a lot of people
我跟很多人成为了朋友，

33
00:01:49.694 --> 00:01:52.846
I never had a chance to talk to before.
之前可能都没有机会说话。

34
00:01:52.870 --> 00:01:56.144
And that included leadership in the Christian Coalition,
包括基督徒联盟的领导层，

35
00:01:56.168 --> 00:02:00.593
often seen as on the right the way MoveOn is seen as on the left.
他们通常被认为是右派， 而MoveON被认为是左派。

36
00:02:00.617 --> 00:02:03.964
And this lead to me showing up on Capitol Hill
于是我去了国会山，

37
00:02:03.988 --> 00:02:08.252
with one of the Christian Coalition leaders, my friend,
跟基督徒联盟的一个领导人， 他是我朋友，

38
00:02:08.276 --> 00:02:10.248
to lobby for net neutrality.
一起游说关于网络中立的问题。

39
00:02:10.272 --> 00:02:11.423
That was powerful.
非常有效。

40
00:02:11.447 --> 00:02:12.825
We turned heads.
我们扭转了局势。

41
00:02:13.735 --> 00:02:17.427
So this work was transformational for me.
这件事给我带来了巨大的转变。

42
00:02:17.817 --> 00:02:20.197
And I found myself wondering:
我开始思考：

43
00:02:20.221 --> 00:02:24.062
How could vast numbers of people have the opportunity
如何才能让大众有机会

44
00:02:24.086 --> 00:02:27.660
to really connect with people that have very different views?
去跟那些与自己有不同观点的人 真正建立联系？

45
00:02:28.792 --> 00:02:30.809
JG: I was born Oneida, Tennessee,
JG：我出生在田纳西州的奥奈达，

46
00:02:30.833 --> 00:02:35.495
right across the state border from a small coal mining town,
穿过州界线，有一个产煤的小镇，

47
00:02:35.519 --> 00:02:36.836
Stearns, Kentucky.
肯塔基州的斯特恩斯。

48
00:02:36.860 --> 00:02:39.376
And I lived there for the first few years of my life,
我出生后头几年都在那儿生活，

49
00:02:38.850 --> 00:02:41.558
before moving to another small town, Frankfort, Kentucky.
后来我又搬到了另一个小镇， 肯塔基州的法兰克福。

50
00:02:41.558 --> 00:02:43.792
Basically, I grew up in small-town America,
基本上我是在美国的小镇长大的，

51
00:02:43.792 --> 00:02:45.676
conservative at its heart.
那里以保守著称。

52
00:02:46.728 --> 00:02:50.394
Now, Stearns and Berkeley -- they're a little different.
当然，斯特恩斯跟伯克利， 还是有那么一点点区别的。

53
00:02:50.418 --> 00:02:52.477
(Laughter)
（笑声）

54
00:02:53.363 --> 00:02:56.975
So in the '90s I moved out west to a progressive area
90年代我搬到了西部， 进步主义的地区，

55
00:02:56.999 --> 00:02:58.526
to work in technology --
在技术行业工作，

56
00:02:58.550 --> 00:03:00.622
worked at Microsoft, worked at Netscape.
在微软，在网景。

57
00:03:00.646 --> 00:03:03.835
I actually became the product manager lead for Netscape Navigator,
后来做了网景导航的 产品经理负责人，

58
00:03:03.859 --> 00:03:05.377
the first popular web browser.
网景导航是第一款主流的浏览器。

59
00:03:06.024 --> 00:03:07.915
Now in the early days of the internet,
在因特网发展早期，

60
00:03:07.939 --> 00:03:11.115
we were just moved and inspired by a vision:
我们都被一个愿景激励和打动：

61
00:03:11.139 --> 00:03:14.386
when we're connected to all these different people around the world
当我们可以将全世界不同的人，

62
00:03:13.350 --> 00:03:15.278
and all these different ideas,
不同的想法都连接起来的时候，

63
00:03:15.952 --> 00:03:17.778
we'll be able to make great decisions,
我们就能做出伟大的决定，

64
00:03:16.888 --> 00:03:19.486
and we'll be able to appreciate each other
就能对世界的多姿多彩

65
00:03:19.846 --> 00:03:22.815
for the beautiful diversity that the whole world has to offer.
心怀感恩之心。

66
00:03:22.839 --> 00:03:24.752
Now I also, 20 years ago, gave a speech
20年前，我还进行过一次演讲，

67
00:03:24.776 --> 00:03:26.608
saying it might not work out that way,
说事情可能并不会这样发展，

68
00:03:27.465 --> 00:03:31.150
that we might actually be trained to discriminate against each other
我们可能会被训练用新的方法

69
00:03:31.174 --> 00:03:32.464
in new ways.
来区别对待对方。

70
00:03:34.177 --> 00:03:35.577
So what happened?
为什么会这样？

71
00:03:36.053 --> 00:03:39.678
It's not like we just woke up one day and decided to hate each other more.
并不是说我们某天醒来， 一拍脑袋决定更加恨彼此。

72
00:03:40.352 --> 00:03:42.045
Here's what happened.
情况是这样的。

73
00:03:42.069 --> 00:03:45.181
There's just too much noise -- too many people, too many ideas --
只不过有太多杂音，太多的人， 太多的主意，

74
00:03:45.205 --> 00:03:47.717
so we use technology to filter it out a little bit.
我们要利用技术过滤掉一些。

75
00:03:47.741 --> 00:03:49.213
And what happens?
结果会怎样呢？

76
00:03:49.237 --> 00:03:51.876
It lets in ideas I already agree with.
它会让我已经认同的观点进入。

77
00:03:51.900 --> 00:03:53.812
It lets in the popular ideas,
让最主流的观点进入，

78
00:03:53.836 --> 00:03:56.630
it lets in people just like me who think just like me.
让跟我类似的人， 跟我思维方式相同的人进入。

79
00:03:56.654 --> 00:03:58.346
That sounds kind of good, right?
听起来很不错，对吗？

80
00:03:58.731 --> 00:04:00.887
Well, not necessarily,
然而并不一定，

81
00:04:00.911 --> 00:04:03.834
because two very scary things happen
因为我们的世界观如此狭隘的话，

82
00:04:03.858 --> 00:04:06.036
when we have such narrow worldviews.
会发生2件很可怕的事情。

83
00:04:06.722 --> 00:04:10.146
First, we become more extreme in our beliefs.
首先，我们对自己所相信的事 会变得偏激。

84
00:04:11.092 --> 00:04:15.729
Second, we become less tolerant of anybody who's different than we are.
其次，我们对于跟自己不同的人 会越来越不宽容。

85
00:04:18.086 --> 00:04:19.669
Does this sound familiar?
听起来是不是有点熟悉？

86
00:04:20.676 --> 00:04:23.609
Does this sound like modern America? The modern world?
这还是现代的美国？现代的世界吗？

87
00:04:24.185 --> 00:04:26.648
Well, the good news is that technology is changing,
但好消息是，技术在变化，

88
00:04:26.672 --> 00:04:28.358
and it could change for the better.
向着好的方向变化。

89
00:04:28.382 --> 00:04:30.819
And that's, in fact, why I started AllSides.com --
这就是我创办AllSides.com的原因，

90
00:04:30.843 --> 00:04:34.588
to create technologies and services to free us from these filter bubbles.
提供技术和服务， 来打破这些过滤气泡。

91
00:04:35.201 --> 00:04:38.773
The very first thing we did was create technology that identifies bias,
我们首先发明了一项技术， 来分辨各种倾向，

92
00:04:38.797 --> 00:04:42.042
so we could show different perspectives side by side
把不同的观点放在一起展示，

93
00:04:42.066 --> 00:04:45.442
to free us from the filter bubbles of news media.
帮我们打破新媒体的过滤气泡。

94
00:04:46.013 --> 00:04:47.950
And then I met Joan.
后来我遇到了琼。

95
00:04:49.111 --> 00:04:52.480
JB: So I met John outside of Washington, DC,
JB：我是在华盛顿郊外遇到的约翰，

96
00:04:52.504 --> 00:04:58.278
with an idealistic group of cross-partisan bridge builders,
他跟一群理想主义者在一起， 希望搭建跨党派交流的桥梁，

97
00:04:58.302 --> 00:05:01.905
and we wanted to re-weave the fabric of our communities.
我们都希望重塑社区的结构。

98
00:05:01.929 --> 00:05:06.330
We believe that our differences can be a strength,
我们相信，我们的不同 能成为一种力量，

99
00:05:06.354 --> 00:05:09.213
that our values can be complimentary
我们的价值观都值得赞美，

100
00:05:09.237 --> 00:05:12.188
and that we have to overcome the fight
我们要终结对抗，

101
00:05:12.212 --> 00:05:14.708
so that we can honor everyone's values
才能尊重彼此的价值观，

102
00:05:14.732 --> 00:05:16.417
and not lose any of our own.
同时也不必放弃自己的价值观。

103
00:05:16.871 --> 00:05:18.901
I went for this wonderful walk with John,
我跟约翰边走边聊，很开心，

104
00:05:18.925 --> 00:05:21.421
where I started learning about the work he was doing
我开始了解他所做的事情，

105
00:05:21.445 --> 00:05:22.921
to pierce the filter bubble.
打破信息过滤的气泡。

106
00:05:23.576 --> 00:05:24.913
It was powerful;
很有力量，

107
00:05:24.937 --> 00:05:26.187
it was brilliant.
天才的想法。

108
00:05:26.957 --> 00:05:30.353
Living in separate narratives is not good.
生活在孤立的舆论中并不好。

109
00:05:30.727 --> 00:05:34.588
We can't even have a conversation or do collaborative problem-solving
如果我们不分享同一件事， 我们甚至无法进行对话，

110
00:05:34.612 --> 00:05:36.936
when we don't share the same facts.
或者合作来解决问题。

111
00:05:38.425 --> 00:05:40.403
JG: So one thing you take away from today
JG：所以今天学到的一件事就是，

112
00:05:40.427 --> 00:05:42.797
is if Joan Blades asks you to go on a walk,
如果琼·布雷兹叫你去散步，

113
00:05:42.821 --> 00:05:44.107
go on that walk.
你一定要去。

114
00:05:44.131 --> 00:05:45.240
(Laughter)
（笑声）

115
00:05:45.788 --> 00:05:49.284
It changed things. It really changed the way I was thinking about things.
这真的带来了改变， 改变了我思考问题的方式。

116
00:05:49.308 --> 00:05:51.402
To free ourselves from the filter bubbles,
把我们从过滤气泡中解救出来，

117
00:05:50.686 --> 00:05:53.090
we can't just think about information filter bubbles,
除了信息过滤气泡，

118
00:05:53.990 --> 00:05:56.678
but also relationship and social filter bubbles.
还有人际关系和社交的过滤气泡。

119
00:05:56.702 --> 00:06:00.162
You see, we human beings -- we're not nearly as smart as we think we are.
我们人类，并没有 自认为的那么聪明。

120
00:06:00.186 --> 00:06:02.643
We don't generally make decisions intellectually.
我们大部分时间 都不会理智地做决定。

121
00:06:02.667 --> 00:06:04.574
We make them emotionally, intuitively,
而是凭感觉，凭直觉，

122
00:06:04.598 --> 00:06:06.319
and then we use our big old brains
然后用我们又大又老的大脑，

123
00:06:05.903 --> 00:06:08.807
to rationalize anything we want to rationalize.
为所有事情找一个合理的解释。

124
00:06:08.781 --> 00:06:12.196
We're not really like Vulcans like Mr. Spock,
我们不像瓦肯人，不像史波克先生，

125
00:06:12.220 --> 00:06:15.582
we're more like bold cowboys like Captain Kirk,
而更像柯克船长那样的冒失牛仔，

126
00:06:15.606 --> 00:06:18.932
or passionate idealists like Dr. McCoy.
或者像麦科伊博士那样 充满激情的理想主义者。

127
00:06:19.324 --> 00:06:22.213
OK, for those of y'all who prefer the new "Star Trek" crew,
好吧，知道你们这些人更喜欢 新《星际迷航》的船员，

128
00:06:21.733 --> 00:06:22.919
here you go.
满足你们。

129
00:06:22.919 --> 00:06:23.963
(Laughter)
（笑声）

130
00:06:23.963 --> 00:06:26.680
JB: Don't forget the strong women!
JB：别忘了坚强的女性们！

131
00:06:26.683 --> 00:06:28.146
JG: Come on, strong women. OK.
JG：好吧，坚强的女性们。来了。

132
00:06:28.170 --> 00:06:29.347
JB: All right.
JB：好的。

133
00:06:29.371 --> 00:06:31.204
John and I are both "Star Trek" fans.
约翰和我都是《星际迷航》的粉丝。

134
00:06:31.228 --> 00:06:35.618
What's not to love about a future with that kind of optimism?
谁会不爱那么乐观的未来呢？

135
00:06:36.315 --> 00:06:39.938
JG: And having a good future in mind is a big deal -- very important.
JG：对未来充满憧憬 是一件大事，非常重要。

136
00:06:39.962 --> 00:06:42.710
And understanding what the problem is is very important.
知道问题出在哪儿，也非常重要。

137
00:06:42.734 --> 00:06:44.112
But we have to do something.
但是我们必须要做点什么。

138
00:06:43.926 --> 00:06:45.349
So what do we do?
我们要怎么做呢？

139
00:06:45.343 --> 00:06:46.693
It's actually not that hard.
其实也没那么难。

140
00:06:46.717 --> 00:06:48.728
We have to add diversity to our lives --
我们要增加生活的多样性，

141
00:06:48.752 --> 00:06:52.069
not just information, but relationship diversity.
不仅仅是信息的多样性， 还有人际关系。

142
00:06:52.093 --> 00:06:54.784
And by diversity, I mean big "D" diversity,
我说的多样性， 本身也是非常“多样”的，

143
00:06:54.808 --> 00:06:57.673
not just racial and gender, which are very important,
不仅在种族和性别方面， 这2者当然非常重要，

144
00:06:57.697 --> 00:06:58.915
but also ...
但还包括，

145
00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:02.360
diversity of age, like young and old;
年龄的多样性， 比如年轻的和年老的，

146
00:07:02.384 --> 00:07:04.583
rural and urban;
农村的和城市的，

147
00:07:04.607 --> 00:07:06.689
liberal and conservative;
自由的和保守的，

148
00:07:07.248 --> 00:07:10.214
in the US, Democrat and Republican.
就美国而言， 也就是民主党人和共和党人。

149
00:07:10.238 --> 00:07:13.470
Now, one of the great examples of somebody freeing themselves
我这儿有一个非常好的例子，

150
00:07:12.144 --> 00:07:14.767
from their filter bubbles
她顺利打破了自己的过滤气泡，

151
00:07:14.761 --> 00:07:16.374
and getting a more diverse life
让自己的生活更加多样化，

152
00:07:16.398 --> 00:07:18.633
is, once again, next to me -- Joan.
还是坐在我身边的这位，琼！

153
00:07:19.371 --> 00:07:20.741
JB: So the question is:
JB：问大家一个问题，

154
00:07:21.208 --> 00:07:25.674
Who among you has had relationships lost or harmed
你们当中有谁，因为政治观点、 宗教信仰或者其他观点的不同，

155
00:07:25.698 --> 00:07:29.280
due to differences in politics, religion or whatever?
而导致关系受损甚至终结？

156
00:07:29.304 --> 00:07:30.627
Raise your hands.
请举一下手。

157
00:07:31.770 --> 00:07:32.928
Yeah.
好吧。

158
00:07:32.952 --> 00:07:35.725
This year I have talked to so many people
近一年来我跟许多人交流过，

159
00:07:35.749 --> 00:07:40.053
that have experienced that kind of loss.
他们都有过类似的经历。

160
00:07:41.307 --> 00:07:45.620
I've seen tears well up in people's eyes as they talk about family members
谈起自己形同陌路的家人，

161
00:07:45.644 --> 00:07:47.183
from whom they're estranged.
他们眼里噙满了泪水。

162
00:07:47.986 --> 00:07:51.684
Living Room Conversations were designed
“起居室对话”设计的初衷

163
00:07:51.708 --> 00:07:57.061
to begin to heal political and personal differences.
是为了弥合政治和个性上的不同。

164
00:07:57.711 --> 00:07:59.423
They're simple conversations
形式很简单，

165
00:07:59.447 --> 00:08:03.066
where two friends with different viewpoints each invite two friends
2个持有不同观点的朋友， 各自再邀请2位朋友，

166
00:08:04.094 --> 00:08:05.710
for structured conversation,
来进行交谈，

167
00:08:05.734 --> 00:08:08.766
where everyone's agreed to some simple ground rules:
每个人都遵守几项基本原则：

168
00:08:08.790 --> 00:08:11.879
curiosity, listening, respect, taking turns --
好奇，倾听，尊重，轮流发言，

169
00:08:11.903 --> 00:08:14.011
everything we learned in kindergarten, right?
这些是我们在幼儿园 就学会了的，对吗？

170
00:08:14.035 --> 00:08:15.310
Really easy.
非常简单。

171
00:08:15.837 --> 00:08:20.703
So by the time you're talking about the topic you've agreed to talk about,
你们讨论着事先定好的话题， 随着交流的继续，

172
00:08:20.727 --> 00:08:22.368
you actually have the sense that,
你慢慢感觉到，

173
00:08:22.392 --> 00:08:24.342
"You know, I kind of like this person,"
“其实，我还挺喜欢这个人的，”

174
00:08:23.946 --> 00:08:26.712
and you listen to each other differently.
于是你倾听的方式都改变了。

175
00:08:26.706 --> 00:08:28.300
That's kind of a human condition;
这就是人类的特点，

176
00:08:28.324 --> 00:08:30.594
we listen differently to people we care about.
对于自己在乎的人， 我们会更愿意倾听。

177
00:08:30.979 --> 00:08:32.955
And then there's reflection
然后你可能有新的想法，

178
00:08:33.640 --> 00:08:35.638
and possibly next steps.
交谈会继续下去。

179
00:08:36.121 --> 00:08:38.760
This is a deep listening practice;
这就是深度倾听的一个实践，

180
00:08:38.784 --> 00:08:40.180
it's never a debate.
并不是要辩论什么。

181
00:08:40.992 --> 00:08:43.162
And that's incredibly powerful.
难以置信的有效。

182
00:08:43.186 --> 00:08:47.500
These conversations in our own living rooms
这些交谈就发生在 我们自己家的起居室，

183
00:08:47.524 --> 00:08:50.217
with people who have different viewpoints
交谈对象是拥有不同观点的人，

184
00:08:50.241 --> 00:08:52.257
are an incredible adventure.
这真的是一场不可思议的冒险。

185
00:08:52.281 --> 00:08:55.700
We rediscover that we can respect and even love people
我们发现，对于跟我们不同的人，

186
00:08:55.724 --> 00:08:57.458
that are different from us.
我们也可以尊重，甚至可以去爱。

187
00:08:57.968 --> 00:08:59.735
And it's powerful.
非常有力量。

188
00:09:00.834 --> 00:09:03.448
JG: So, what are you curious about?
JG：那么，你们对什么感到好奇？

189
00:09:03.881 --> 00:09:06.595
JB: What's the conversation you yearn to have?
JB：你们渴望进行一场 什么样的对话？

190
00:09:07.019 --> 00:09:08.414
JG: Let's do this together.
JG：我们一起努力吧。

191
00:09:08.997 --> 00:09:10.147
Together.
一起努力。

192
00:09:10.518 --> 00:09:11.669
JB: Yes.
JB：好的！

193
00:09:11.693 --> 00:09:12.716
(Laughter)
（笑声）

194
00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:14.930
(Applause)
（掌声）

195
00:09:14.954 --> 00:09:16.114
JB and JG: Thank you.
JB&amp;JG：谢谢大家。